13 “Overburdened community” means a census block group in Massachusetts that meets the
14 following criteria:
15 (1) Is at or above the 75th statewide percentile for at least 2 of the following
16 environmental indicators on the most recent available United States Environmental Protection
17 Agency’s EJSCREEN assessment: (a) PM 2.5; (b) ozone; (c) NATA diesel PM; (d) NATA
18 cancer risk; (e) NATA respiratory hazard index; (f) traffic proximity; (g) lead paint indicator; (h)
19 superfund proximity; (i) risk management plan facilities proximity; (j) hazardous waste
20 proximity; and (k) wastewater discharge indicator; and
21 (2) has a median household income that is no greater than 80% of the statewide median
22 household income as calculated by the US Census Bureau.
23 (b) The department shall create the food justice frontline program.
24 (c) The food justice frontline program shall fund nonprofit food security organizations for
25 the purpose of creating and sustaining food security jobs to individuals living within
26 overburdened communities.
27 (d) The department shall create an application with which nonprofit food security
28 organizations may apply to receive a financial grant, not to exceed $500,000.
29 (e) In order to be eligible for the food justice frontline program, the nonprofit food
30 security organization must submit an application that includes, but is not necessarily limited to:
31 (1) a detailed description of the program or programs which the nonprofit food security
32 organization operates that provide land or food security jobs to low-income Massachusetts
33 residents; and (2) a detailed description of the ways in which the nonprofit food security
2 of 4

34 organization would use funding to create jobs for individuals living within overburdened
35 communities.
36 (f) The department shall establish regulations and guidelines regarding the process and
37 criteria for approval of applications for the food justice frontline program. These regulations and
38 guidelines shall prioritize applications from nonprofit food security organizations which
39 demonstrate a clear and credible plan to quickly create food security jobs for individuals living
40 within overburdened communities.
41 (g) Nonprofit food security organizations which receive a grant under the food justice
42 frontline program must use the entirety of the grant money on programs which will create food
43 security jobs for individuals living within overburdened communities. These jobs must pay an
44 hourly wage of not less than the quotient of one divided by two thousand and four hundred
45 (1/2,400), multiplied by the statewide per capita income, as calculated by the United States
46 Census Bureau.
47 (h) A nonprofit food security organization may apply for multiple financial grants under
48 the food justice frontline program.
49 (i) The department shall have the power to enter contracts, hire employees, hire
50 contractors, promulgate rules and regulations, adjudicate administrative cases, or take any other
51 lawful action in order to implement the food justice frontline program.
52 Section 2D. (a) The department, in consultation with the executive office of economic
53 development and the executive office of housing and liveable communities, shall establish a
54 program designed to increase public awareness of the availability of the supplemental nutrition
55 assistance program, the healthy incentives program, and other similar food access programs for
3 of 4

56 low-income Massachusetts residents and food insecure Massachusetts residents.The department
57 shall employ Massachusetts residents under the age of eighteen to promote public awareness of
58 the supplemental nutrition assistance program. The department shall prioritize working with
59 Massachusetts residents who live in overburdened communities or census block groups with a
60 median household income that is below 80% of the statewide median household income. This
61 program shall be conducted in languages which reflect the native languages spoken by members
62 of relevant overburdened communities.
63 (b) The department may apply for any relevant federal programs administered by the
64 United States department of agriculture to provide matching benefits to be deposited in the fund.
65 (c) The department shall promulgate rules and regulations to implement this program.
